# 🧩 Backend (Node.js + Express example)

> This pattern is identical in **Spring Boot**, only syntax differs.

## 1️⃣ Install

```bash
npm install express cookie-parser cors uuid
```

***

## 2️⃣ `server.js`

```js
import express from "express";
import cookieParser from "cookie-parser";
import cors from "cors";
import { v4 as uuid } from "uuid";

const app = express();
app.use(express.json());
app.use(cookieParser());

app.use(cors({
  origin: "http://localhost:5173",
  credentials: true
}));
```

***

## 🔐 Login – set session cookie + CSRF cookie

```js
app.post("/login", (req, res) => {
  // Imagine user authenticated here ✅
  const sessionId = uuid();
  const csrfToken = uuid();

  // Session cookie (HttpOnly)
  res.cookie("SESSIONID", sessionId, {
    httpOnly: true,
    sameSite: "lax",
    secure: false, // true in production
    path: "/"
  });

  // CSRF token cookie (JS-readable)
  res.cookie("CSRF-TOKEN", csrfToken, {
    httpOnly: false,
    sameSite: "lax",
    secure: false,
    path: "/"
  });

  res.json({ message: "Logged in" });
});
```

✅ `SESSIONID` → JS **cannot read**\
✅ `CSRF-TOKEN` → JS **can read**

***

## 🛡 CSRF Protection Middleware (CORE)

```js
function csrfProtection(req, res, next) {
  const csrfCookie = req.cookies["CSRF-TOKEN"];
  const csrfHeader = req.headers["x-csrf-token"];

  if (!csrfCookie || !csrfHeader) {
    return res.status(403).json({ message: "CSRF missing" });
  }

  if (csrfCookie !== csrfHeader) {
    return res.status(403).json({ message: "CSRF invalid" });
  }

  next();
}
```

✅ Double‑submit verification\
✅ Cookie + header must match

***

## 🔒 Protected API (CSRF‑secured)

```js
app.post("/transfer", csrfProtection, (req, res) => {
  res.json({ message: "Money transferred safely ✅" });
});
```

